{"title":"FlashAudio: Rectified Flows for Fast and High-fidelity Text-to-Audio Generation","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Diffusion-based and consistency-distilled text-to-audio systems require many iterative steps, and curved probability paths make few-/one-step generation inaccurate and slow for real-time use.","method":"FlashAudio adopts rectified flows to learn straight transport paths for text-conditioned audio latents. It initializes from a strong pre-trained conditional flow matching model, then applies a single reflow step to obtain a near-straight 2-rectified flow ODE, and finally performs one-step distillation to compress the ODE solution into a single Euler step. This yields fast few-step and one-step generation that surpasses diffusion models using hundreds of steps in audio quality, with RTF≈0.0025 (~400× faster than real time) and improved metrics (e.g., lower FAD, higher CLAP)."},{"problem":"Uniform timestep sampling in rectified flow training wastes capacity on easy regions, and arbitrary pairing between Gaussian noise and data creates mixing/ambiguity that hinders stable learning.","method":"FlashAudio introduces Bifocal Samplers to reweight training timesteps: a logit-normal distribution prioritizes challenging mid-range t for 1-RF, while a mixture-of-exponentials emphasizes boundary regions near noise/data for reflow (2-RF). It further proposes Immiscible Flow, which assigns batches of noise to audio samples by minimizing total pairwise distances (Hungarian algorithm), preserving Gaussianity while reducing confusion in mappings. Ablations show these choices improve KL/CLAP and FAD versus uniform sampling and unassigned noise (e.g., 2-RF Mix-Exp vs w/o Mix-Exp; and w/ vs w/o immiscible flow)."},{"problem":"Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG) with large guidance scales amplifies simulation/regression errors in rectified flows and perturbs the marginal distribution, degrading audio quality and text-audio alignment.","method":"Anchored Optimization uses an ω=1 simulation as a pivot trajectory and, during paired generation for reflow and distillation, optimizes only the unconditional embedding around this anchor while sampling with ω>1, keeping model weights and textual embeddings fixed. The model then regresses to the guided velocity field v_cfg, enabling stronger guidance without destabilizing the flow. This improves quality and alignment (e.g., FAD 1.43→1.26, CLAP 0.639→0.652) compared to naive CFG in RF."}]}
